# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bacterioplankton
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Research suggests that all currently known AAPB contain Gram-negative cell walls.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] The majority have shapes that resemble cylinders, as well as flagella and pili.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] AAP bacteria are motile due to one polar or subpolar flagellum.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Species of these bacteria such as *Roseobacter denitrificans* and *Sandaracinobacter sibiricus* have up to three subpolar flagella.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] AAPB cell dimensions are normally, 1.2 μm long, 0.7 μm in diameter, and a cell volume of 0.5 μm3.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Their dry weight is 0.05 pg and wet weight is 0.5 pg.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] 3 types of cell division are known to exist within AAPB, 2 daughter-cell division, 4 daughter-cell division, and the non-typical 3 daughter-cell division, commonly referred to as Y-cell division.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] AAPB are usually pink or orange in color when isolated from water.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Current data suggests that marine bacteria have generation times of several days, whereas new evidence exists that shows AAPB to have a much shorter generation time.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] All species of AAPB produce large amounts of carotenoid pigments.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] The color of each species is due to the presence of carotenoids, giving peaks in the blue and green absorption spectra.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Light harvesting complexes with unusual absorption maxima have been discovered due to the isolation and characterization of new aerobic phototrophic species.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] A new strain of aerobic anoxygenic phototrophic bacteria, JF-1, was recently isolated from deep-ocean hydrothermal vent waters.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] These bacteria were found to be pleomorphic which shapes varying from coccoid and ovoid rods, to bean-shaped.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] The coccoid bacteria were from 0.4 to 0.5 μm in size.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] The ovoid rods were 0.4 to 0.5 μm in diameter, and 1.0 to 1.2 μm in length.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Thread-like formations of up to five bacterial cells were also observed in these vents.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Aerobic anoxygenic phototrophic bacteria are divided into two groups; there are two marine genera (*Erythrobacter* and *Roseobacter*), and five freshwater genera (Acidiphilium, *Blastomonas* (synonym: *Erythromonas*), *Erythrobacter*, *Roseococcus*, and *Sandaracinobacter*).
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Most AAP bacteria belong to subgroups of Alphaproteobacteria, but some species are known within the Betaproteobacteria and Gammaproteobacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Additionally, *Chloracidobacterium thermophilum* and *Gemmatimonas phototrophica* are recently characterized species of AAPB within the phyla Acidobacteria and Gemmatimonadota, respectively.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Of phototrophic prokaryotes in the ocean, AAP bacteria are the third most numerous group.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] AAPB play a key role in carbon cycling but to what extent is still being investigated.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Since AAPB themselves lack a way to fix carbon, they instead rely on organic matter substrates as a carbon source.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Because of this, AAPB are now thought to play an important role in the sequestration of total organic carbon, and act as sinks for dissolved organic carbon.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] AAPB have also been found to act as sources of total organic carbon in some freshwater systems and to be producers of carbon at groundwater-surface water exchange systems.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] AAPB are widely distributed in coastal and oceanic environments.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] AAPB may constitute over 10% of the open ocean microbial community, being particularly abundant in oligotrophic conditions where they were found to make up around 24% of the microbes present.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] One study revealed that the surface water of the Indian Ocean ranked the highest of the oceans in AAPB% at 3.79, followed by the Atlantic Ocean (1.57 AAPB%) and the Pacific Ocean (1.08 AAPB%).
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] There was a positive correlation with oceans that held higher values of AAPB% and those with higher levels of chlorophyll *a*.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] More specifically, the coastal/shelf waters of these oceans had greater amounts of AAPB, some as high as 13.51% AAPB%.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Phytoplankton also affect AAPB%, but little research has been performed in this area.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] They can also be abundant in various oligotrophic conditions, including the most oligotrophic regime of the world ocean.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] They are globally distributed in the euphotic zone and represent a hitherto unrecognized component of the marine microbial community that appears to be critical to the cycling of both organic and inorganic carbon in the ocean.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Aerobic phototrophic bacteria are unable to be isolated on selective medium.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Instead, these bacteria are indicated by the colony color due to presence of carotenoids.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Aerobic phototrophic bacteria can be isolated using media that are rich in organic compounds using direct inoculation of water samples or sand samples.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Inoculated plates are prepared in conditions similar to the natural environments of the collected sample to increase survivability of the bacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] The presence of Bchl *a* is what separates these bacteria from other heterotrophic bacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Aerobic phototrophic species can remain viable for at least 2 months when stored at 4 °C in liquid or on agar surfaces.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] They can also be preserved long-term by storing in liquid nitrogen or at temperatures -70 °C and below.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Compared to most other bacteria in their natural environment, AAPB have a relatively large predation pressure, resulting in high growth rates which balance out the high level of grazing they experience.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] The removal of predators and this grazing pressure results in a large increase in AAP relative to the other bacteria in the environment.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Additionally, phosphorus has been identified as a common limiting factor in AAPB growth, which has been shown to sometimes be a stronger limiting factor to AABP growth than predation.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Light availability has also been shown to be a factor that stimulates AAPB population growth.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] One effect light has on AAP that has been linked to increased growth is that it has been shown to increase the membrane potential of the bacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/aerobic-anoxygenic-phototrophic-bacteria] Increased light exposure has also been shown to extenuate the growth rate increase caused by removal of predators and the amendment of phosphorus levels.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Transmission of furunculosis mainly occurs through fish-to-fish contact by the skin or by ingestion.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Rainbow trout have been found to carry *A. salmonicida* up to two years after initial infection without re-exposure.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Chemically immunosuppressed fish compared with temperature-stressed fish had a 73% mortality as opposed to a 33% mortality rate, respectively.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Naturally occurring trout infections consisted of a 5–6% mortality rate per week with an 85% rate in untreated populations.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Some clinical furunculosis survivors of an infected trout population became *A. salmonicida* carriers.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] When comparing furunculosis epidemics with depressed oxygen levels, when oxygen concentrations were decreased to less than 5 mg/L, *A. salmonicida* concentrations increased.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] While observing chum salmon in a density of 14.7 fish per square meter, 12.4% were infected with *A. salmonicida*, whereas, densities at 4.9 fish per square meter were infection-free.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Additionally, *A. salmonicida* concentrations were considerably elevated in water with low dissolved oxygen (6–7 mg/L), compared to water with higher dissolved oxygen (10 mg/L).
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] High density-low oxygen water resulted in survival rates that were roughly 40% less than in those consisting of low density-high oxygen conditions.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] The bacterium is pathogenic for fish, and causes the disease known as furunculosis.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] The symptoms the fish show are external and internal hemorrhaging, swelling of the vents and kidneys, boils, ulcers, liquefaction, and gastroenteritis.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Furunculosis is commonly known as tail rot in fish and is common in goldfish and koi.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Infected fish with open sores are able to spread the disease to other fish.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] It is also one of several bacteria that can cause bald sea urchin disease.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Since *A. salmonicida* cannot grow at 37 °C, it is not pathogenic in humans.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Furunculosis is classified into four categories based on severity: acute, subacute, chronic, or latent.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] When fish are infected, they become listless and weak until they die.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Other characteristics observed include anorexia and lethargic movement, and they may exhibit a darkened pigment.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Deep or shallow ulcers, exophthalmia, bloody spots, distended abdomen, and petechia at the base of the fin may also occur.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Internally, the infected fish may suffer from gastroenteritis, hemorrhagic septicemia, edematous kidney, and an enlarged spleen.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] The liver may appear pale in color and the spleen may be darkened.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] The peritoneal cavity may also be bloody and inflamed.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Bacteria must be isolated to positively identify the disease.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Isolates are retrieved from muscle lesions, kidney, spleen, or liver, and then grown on trypticase soy agar and brain-heart infusion medium incubated at 20–25 °C.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Colonies of *A. salmonicida* appear hard, friable, smooth, soft, and dark in color.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] While cultural procedures produce good results, serological procedures produce more rapid results by using serum agglutination, fluorescent antibody, or enzyme linked immunosorbent assay on infected tissue or cultured bacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeromonas-salmonicida] Mooney *et al.* developed a DNA probe with polymerase chain reaction to detect *A. salmonicida* DNA; results were successful in 88% of wild Atlantic salmon.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Additionally, microorganisms are swept into the air from terrestrial dust storms, and an even larger amount of airborne marine microorganisms are propelled high into the atmosphere in sea spray.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Aeroplankton deposits hundreds of millions of airborne viruses and tens of millions of bacteria every day on every square meter around the planet.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Small, drifting aeroplankton are found everywhere in the atmosphere, reaching concentration up to 106 microbial cells per cubic metre.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Processes such as aerosolization and wind transport determine how the microorganisms are distributed in the atmosphere.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Air mass circulation globally disperses vast numbers of the floating aerial organisms, which travel across and between continents, creating biogeographic patterns by surviving and settling in remote environments.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] As well as the colonization of pristine environments, the globetrotting behaviour of these organisms has human health consequences.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Airborne microorganisms are also involved in cloud formation and precipitation, and play important roles in the formation of the phyllosphere, a vast terrestrial habitat involved in nutrient cycling.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The atmosphere is the least understood biome on Earth despite its critical role as a microbial transport medium.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Recent studies have shown microorganisms are ubiquitous in the atmosphere and reach concentration up to 106 microbial cells per cubic metre (28,000/cu ft) and that they might be metabolically active.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Different processes, such as aerosolisation, might be important in selecting which microorganisms exist in the atmosphere.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Another process, microbial transport in the atmosphere, is critical for understanding the role microorganisms play in meteorology, atmospheric chemistry and public health.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Changes in species geographic distributions can have strong ecological and socioeconomic consequences.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In the case of microorganisms, air mass circulation disperses vast amounts of individuals and interconnects remote environments.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Airborne microorganisms can travel between continents, survive and settle on remote environments, which creates biogeographic patterns.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The circulation of atmospheric microorganisms results in global health concerns and ecological processes such as widespread dispersal of both pathogens and antibiotic resistances, cloud formation and precipitation, and colonization of pristine environments.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Airborne microorganisms also play a role in the formation of the phyllosphere, which is one of the vastest habitats on the Earth's surface involved in nutrient cycling.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The field of bioaerosol research studies the taxonomy and community composition of airborne microbial organisms, also referred to as the air microbiome.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] A recent series of technological and analytical advancements include high-volumetric air samplers, an ultra-low biomass processing pipeline, low-input DNA sequencing libraries, as well as high-throughput sequencing technologies.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Applied in unison, these methods have enabled comprehensive and meaningful characterization of the airborne microbial organismal dynamics found in the near-surface atmosphere.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Airborne microbial organisms also impact agricultural productivity, as bacterial and fungal species distributed by air movement act as plant blights.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Furthermore, atmospheric processes, such as cloud condensation and ice nucleation events were shown to depend on airborne microbial particles.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Therefore, understanding the dynamics of microbial organisms in air is crucial for insights into the atmosphere as an ecosystem, but also will inform on human wellbeing and respiratory health.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In recent years, next generation DNA sequencing technologies, such as metabarcoding as well as coordinated metagenomics and metatranscriptomics studies, have been providing new insights into microbial ecosystem functioning, and the relationships that microorganisms maintain with their environment.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] There have been studies in soils, the ocean, the human gut, and elsewhere.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In the atmosphere, though, microbial gene expression and metabolic functioning remain largely unexplored, in part due to low biomass and sampling difficulties.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] So far, metagenomics has confirmed high fungal, bacterial, and viral biodiversity, and targeted genomics and transcriptomics towards ribosomal genes has supported earlier findings about the maintenance of metabolic activity in aerosols and in clouds.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In atmospheric chambers airborne bacteria have been consistently demonstrated to react to the presence of a carbon substrate by regulating ribosomal gene expressions.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Effective pollen dispersal is vital for maintenance of genetic diversity and fundamental for connectivity between spatially separated populations.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] An efficient transfer of the pollen guarantees successful reproduction in flowering plants.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] No matter how pollen is dispersed, the male-female recognition is possible by mutual contact of stigma and pollen surfaces.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Cytochemical reactions are responsible for pollen binding to a specific stigma.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Allergic diseases are considered to be one of the most important contemporary public health problems affecting up to 15–35% of humans worldwide.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] There is a body of evidence suggesting that allergic reactions induced by pollen are on the increase, particularly in highly industrial countries.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Fungi, a major element of atmospheric bioaerosols, are capable of existing and surviving in the air for extended periods of time.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Both the spores and the mycelium may be dangerous for people suffering from allergies, causing various health issues including asthma.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Apart from their negative impact on human health, atmospheric fungi may be dangerous for plants as sources of infection.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Moreover, fungal organisms may be capable of creating additional toxins that are harmful to humans and animals, such as endotoxins or mycotoxins.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Considering this aspect, aeromycological research is considered capable of predicting future symptoms of plant diseases in both crops and wild plants.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Fungi capable of travelling extensive distances with wind despite natural barriers, such as tall mountains, may be particularly relevant to understanding the role of fungi in plant disease.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Notably, the presence of numerous fungal organisms pathogenic to plants has been determined in mountainous regions.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] A wealth of correlative evidence suggests asthma is associated with fungi and triggered by elevated numbers of fungal spores in the environment.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Intriguing are reports of thunderstorm asthma.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In a now classic study from the United Kingdom, an outbreak of acute asthma was linked to increases in *Didymella exitialis* ascospores and *Sporobolomyces* basidiospores associated with a severe weather event.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Thunderstorms are associated with spore plumes: when spore concentrations increase dramatically over a short period of time, for example from 20,000 spores/m3 to over 170,000 spores/m3 in 2 hours.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] However, other sources consider pollen or pollution as causes of thunderstorm asthma.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Transoceanic and transcontinental dust events move large numbers of spores across vast distances and have the potential to impact public health, and similar correlative evidence links dust blown off the Sahara with pediatric emergency room admissions on the island of Trinidad.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Pteridophytes are vascular plants that disperse spores, such as fern spores.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Pteridophyte spores are similar to pollen grains and fungal spores, and are also components of aeroplankton.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Fungal spores usually rank first among bioaerosol constituents due to their count numbers which can reach to between 1,000 and 10,000 per cubic metre (28 and 283/cu ft), while pollen grains and fern spores can each reach to between 10 and 100 per cubic metre (0.28 and 2.83/cu ft).
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Many small animals, mainly arthropods (such as insects and spiders), are also carried upwards into the atmosphere by air currents and may be found floating several thousand feet up.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Aphids, for example, are frequently found at high altitudes.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Ballooning, sometimes called kiting, is a process by which spiders, and some other small invertebrates, move through the air by releasing one or more gossamer threads to catch the wind, causing them to become airborne at the mercy of air currents.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] A spider (usually limited to individuals of a small species), or spiderling after hatching, will climb as high as it can, stand on raised legs with its abdomen pointed upwards ("tiptoeing"), and then release several silk threads from its spinnerets into the air.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] These automatically form a triangular shaped parachute which carries the spider away on updrafts of winds where even the slightest of breezes will disperse the arachnid.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The flexibility of their silk draglines can aid the aerodynamics of their flight, causing the spiders to drift an unpredictable and sometimes long distance.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Even atmospheric samples collected from balloons at 5 km (3.1 mi) altitude and ships mid-ocean have reported spider landings.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Enough lift for ballooning may occur, even in windless conditions, if an electrostatic charge gradient is present in the atmosphere.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Nematodes (roundworms), the most common animal taxon, are also found among aeroplankton.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Nematodes are an essential trophic link between unicellular organisms like bacteria, and larger organisms such as tardigrades, copepods, flatworms, and fishes.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] For nematodes, anhydrobiosis is a widespread strategy allowing them to survive unfavorable conditions for months and even years.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Accordingly, nematodes can be readily dispersed by wind.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] However, as reported by Vanschoenwinkel et al., nematodes account for only about one per cent of wind-drifted animals.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Among the habitats colonized by nematodes are those that are strongly exposed to wind erosion as e.g., the shorelines of permanent waters, soils, mosses, dead wood, and tree bark.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In addition, within a few days of forming temporary waters such as phytotelmata were shown to be colonized by numerous nematode species.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] A stream of unicellular airborne microorganisms circles the planet above weather systems but below commercial air lanes.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Some microorganisms are swept up from terrestrial dust storms, but most originate from marine microorganisms in sea spray.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In 2018, scientists reported that hundreds of millions of viruses and tens of millions of bacteria are deposited daily on every square meter around the planet.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The presence of airborne cyanobacteria and microalgae as well as their negative impacts on human health have been documented by many researchers worldwide.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] However, studies on cyanobacteria and microalgae are few compared with those on other bacteria and viruses.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Research is especially lacking on the presence and taxonomic composition of cyanobacteria and microalgae near economically important water bodies with much tourism.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Research on airborne algae is especially important in tourist areas near water-bodies.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Sunbathers are exposed to particularly high quantities of harmful cyanobacteria and microalgae.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Additionally, harmful microalgae and cyanobacteria blooms tend to occur in both marine and freshwater reservoirs during summer.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Previous work has shown that the Mediterranean Sea is dominated by the picocyanobacteria *Synechococcus* sp. and *Synechocystis* sp., which are responsible for the production of a group of hepatotoxins known as microcystins.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Because most tourism occurs in summer, many tourists are exposed to the most extreme negative impacts of airborne microalgae.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Airborne bacteria are emitted by most Earth surfaces (plants, oceans, land, and urban areas) to the atmosphere via a variety of mechanical processes such as aeolian soil erosion, sea spray production, or mechanical disturbances including anthropogenic activities.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Due to their relatively small size (the median aerodynamic diameter of bacteria-containing particles is around 2–4 μm), these can then be transported upward by turbulent fluxes and carried by wind to long distances.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] As a consequence, bacteria are present in the air up to at least the lower stratosphere.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Given that the atmosphere is a large conveyor belt that moves air over thousands of kilometers, microorganisms are disseminated globally.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Airborne transport of microbes is therefore likely pervasive at the global scale, yet there have been only a limited number of studies that have looked at the spatial distribution of microbes across different geographical regions.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] One of the main difficulties is linked with the low microbial biomass associated with a high diversity existing in the atmosphere outdoor (~102–105 cells/m3) thus requiring reliable sampling procedures and controls.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Furthermore, the site location and its environmental specificities have to be accounted for to some extent by considering chemical and meteorological variables.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The environmental role of airborne cyanobacteria and microalgae is only partly understood.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] While present in the air, cyanobacteria and microalgae can contribute to ice nucleation and cloud droplet formation.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Cyanobacteria and microalgae can also impact human health.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Depending on their size, airborne cyanobacteria and microalgae can be inhaled by humans and settle in different parts of the respiratory system, leading to the formation or intensification of numerous diseases and ailments, e.g., allergies, dermatitis, and rhinitis.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] According to Wiśniewska et al., these harmful microorganisms can constitute between 13% and 71% of sampled taxa.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] However, the interplay between microbes and atmospheric physical and chemical conditions is an open field of research that can only be fully addressed using multidisciplinary approaches.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Airborne microalgae and cyanobacteria are the most poorly studied organisms in aerobiology and phycology.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] This lack of knowledge may result from the lack of standard methods for both sampling and further analysis, especially quantitative analytical methods.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Few studies have been performed to determine the number of cyanobacteria and microalgae in the atmosphere However, it was shown in 2012 that the average quantity of atmospheric algae is between 100 and 1000 cells per cubic meter of air.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] As of 2019, about 350 taxa of cyanobacteria and microalgae have been documented in the atmosphere worldwide.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Cyanobacteria and microalgae end up in the air as a consequence of their emission from soil, buildings, trees, and roofs.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The bacterium *Pseudomonas syringae* can manufacture ice nucleation active (INA) proteins (which cause water in plants to freeze at temperatures higher than normal freezing point).
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In airborne versions of *P. syringae*, these proteins serve as atmospheric biological ice nucleators, so the bacteria can function as cloud condensation nuclei.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Recent evidence has suggested the species plays a larger role than previously thought in producing rain and snow.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] They have also been found in the cores of hailstones, aiding in bioprecipitation.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Biological particles are known to represent a significant fraction (~20–70%) of the total number of aerosols > 0.2 μm, with large spatial and temporal variations.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Among these, microorganisms are of particular interest in fields as diverse as epidemiology, including phytopathology, bioterrorism, forensic science, and public health, and environmental sciences, like microbial ecology, meteorology and climatology.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] More precisely concerning the latter, airborne microorganisms contribute to the pool of particles nucleating the condensation and crystallization of water and they are thus potentially involved in cloud formation and in the triggering of precipitation.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Additionally, viable microbial cells act as chemical catalyzers interfering with atmospheric chemistry.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The constant flux of bacteria from the atmosphere to the Earth's surface due to precipitation and dry deposition can also affect global biodiversity, but they are rarely taken into account when conducting ecological surveys.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] As stressed by these studies attempting to decipher and understand the spread of microbes over the planet, concerted data are needed for documenting the abundance and distribution of airborne microorganisms, including at remote and altitudes sites.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Bioaerosols, known also as primary biological aerosols, are the subset of atmospheric particles that are directly released from the biosphere into the atmosphere.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] They include living and dead organisms (e.g., algae, archaea, bacteria ), dispersal units (e.g., fungal spores and plant pollen ), and various fragments or excretions (e.g., plant debris and brochosomes).
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Bioaerosol particle diameters range from nanometers up to about a tenth of a millimeter.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The upper limit of the aerosol particle size range is determined by rapid sedimentation, i.e., larger particles are too heavy to remain airborne for extended periods of time.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Bioaerosols include living and dead organisms as well as their fragments and excrements emitted from the biosphere into the atmosphere.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Included are archaea, fungi, microalgae, cyanobacteria, bacteria, viruses, plant cell debris, and pollen.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Historically, the first investigations of the occurrence and dispersion of microorganisms and spores in the air can be traced back to the early 19th century.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Bioaerosols play a key role in the dispersal of reproductive units from plants and microbes (pollen, spores, etc.), for which the atmosphere enables transport over geographic barriers and long distances.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Bioaerosols are thus highly relevant for the spread of organisms, allowing genetic exchange between habitats and geographic shifts of biomes.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] They are central elements in the development, evolution, and dynamics of ecosystems.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Dispersal is a vital component of an organism's life-history, and the potential for dispersal determines the distribution, abundance, and thus, the community dynamics of species at different sites.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] A new habitat must first be reached before filters such as organismal abilities and adaptations, the quality of a habitat, and the established biological community determine the colonization efficiency of a species.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] While larger animals can cover distances on their own and actively seek suitable habitats, small (<2 mm) organisms are often passively dispersed, resulting in their more ubiquitous occurrence.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] While active dispersal accounts for rather predictable distribution patterns, passive dispersal leads to a more randomized immigration of organisms.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Mechanisms for passive dispersal are the transport on (epizoochory) or in (endozoochory) larger animals (e.g., flying insects, birds, or mammals) and the erosion by wind.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] A propagule is any material that functions in propagating an organism to the next stage in its life cycle, such as by dispersal.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The propagule is usually distinct in form from the parent organism.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Propagules are produced by plants (in the form of seeds or spores), fungi (in the form of spores), and bacteria (for example endospores or microbial cysts).
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Often cited as an important requirement for effective wind dispersal is the presence of propagules (e.g., resting eggs, cysts, ephippia, juvenile and adult resting stages), which also enables organisms to survive unfavorable environmental conditions until they enter a suitable habitat.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] These dispersal units can be blown from surfaces such as soil, moss, and the desiccated sediments of temporary or intermittent waters.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The passively dispersed organisms are typically pioneer colonizers.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] However, wind-drifted species vary in their vagility (probability to be transported with the wind), with the weight and form of the propagules, and therefore, the wind speed required for their transport, determining the dispersal distance.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] For example, in nematodes, resting eggs are less effectively transported by wind than other life stages, while organisms in anhydrobiosis are lighter and thus more readily transported than hydrated forms.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Because different organisms are, for the most part, not dispersed over the same distances, source habitats are also important, with the number of organisms contained in air declining with increasing distance from the source system.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The distances covered by small animals range from a few meters, to hundreds, to thousands of meters.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] While the wind dispersal of aquatic organisms is possible even during the wet phase of a transiently aquatic habitat, during the dry stages a larger number of dormant propagules are exposed to wind and thus dispersed.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Freshwater organisms that must "cross the dry ocean" to enter new aquatic island systems will be passively dispersed more successfully than terrestrial taxa.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Numerous taxa from both soil and freshwater systems have been captured from the air (e.g., bacteria, several algae, ciliates, flagellates, rotifers, crustaceans, mites, and tardigrades).
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] While these have been qualitatively well studied, accurate estimates of their dispersal rates are lacking.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Once aerosolized, microbial cells enter the planetary boundary layer, defined as the air layer near the ground directly influenced by the planetary surface.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The concentration and taxonomic diversity of airborne microbial communities in the planetary boundary layer has been recently described, though the functional potential of airborne microbial communities remains unknown.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] From the planetary boundary layer, the microbial community might eventually be transported upwards by air currents into the free troposphere (air layer above the planetary boundary layer) or even higher into the stratosphere.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Microorganisms might undergo a selection process during their way up into the troposphere and the stratosphere.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Subject to gravity, aerosols (or particulate matter) as well as bioaerosols become concentrated in the lower part of the troposphere that is called the planetary boundary layer.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The various atmospheric phases represent multiple biological niches.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Possible processes in the way atmospheric microbial communities can distribute themselves have recently been investigated in meteorology, seasons, surface conditions and global air circulation.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Microorganisms attached to aerosols can travel intercontinental distances, survive, and further colonize remote environments.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Airborne microbes are influenced by environmental and climatic patterns that are predicted to change in the near future, with unknown consequences.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Airborne microbial communities play significant roles in public health and meteorological processes, so it is important to understand how these communities are distributed over time and space.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Most studies have focused on laboratory cultivation to identify possible metabolic functions of microbial strains of atmospheric origin, mainly from cloud water.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] There are some metagenomic studies on airborne microbial communities over specific sites.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] This observed correlation of microbial-community functional potential and the physical and chemical characteristics of their environments could have resulted from genetic modifications (microbial adaptation ) and/or physical selection.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The latter refers to the death of sensitive cells and the survival of resistant or previously adapted cells.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] This physical selection can occur when microorganisms are exposed to physiologically adverse conditions.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The presence of a specific microbial functional signature in the atmosphere has not been investigated yet.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Microbial strains of airborne origin have been shown to survive and develop under conditions typically found in cloud water (i.e., high concentrations of H2O2, typical cloud carbonaceous sources, ultraviolet – UV – radiation etc.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] While atmospheric chemicals might lead to some microbial adaptation, physical and unfavorable conditions of the atmosphere such as UV radiation, low water content and cold temperatures might select which microorganisms can survive in the atmosphere.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] From the pool of microbial cells being aerosolized from Earth's surfaces, these adverse conditions might act as a filter in selecting cells already resistant to unfavorable physical conditions.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Fungal cells and especially fungal spores might be particularly adapted to survive in the atmosphere due to their innate resistance and might behave differently than bacterial cells.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Still, the proportion and nature (i.e., fungi versus bacteria) of microbial cells that are resistant to the harsh atmospheric conditions within airborne microbial communities are unknown.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Airborne microbial transport is central to dispersal outcomes and several studies have demonstrated diverse microbial biosignatures are recoverable from the atmosphere.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Microbial transport has been shown to occur across inter-continental distances above terrestrial habitats.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Variation has been recorded seasonally, with underlying land use, and due to stochastic weather events such as dust storms.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] There is evidence specific bacterial taxa (e.g., Actinomycetota and some Gammaproteobacteria) are preferentially aerosolized from oceans.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] As a result of rapid industrialization and urbanization, global megacities have been impacted by extensive and intense particulate matter pollution events, which have potential human health consequences.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Severe particulate matter pollution is associated with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and asthma, as well as risks for early death.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] While the chemical components of particulate matter pollution and their impacts on human health have been widely studied, the potential impact of pollutant-associated microbes remains unclear.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Airborne microbial exposure, including exposure to dust-associated organisms, has been established to both protect against and exacerbate certain diseases.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Understanding the temporal dynamics of the taxonomic and functional diversity of microorganisms in urban air, especially during smog events, will improve understanding of the potential microbe-associated health consequences.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Recent advances in airborne particle DNA extraction and metagenomic library preparation have enabled low biomass environments to be subject to shotgun sequencing analysis.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In 2020, Qin *et al.* used shotgun sequencing analysis to reveal a great diversity of microbial species and antibiotic resistant genes in Beijing's particulate matter, largely consistent with a recent study.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The data suggest that potential pathogen and antibiotic resistance burden increases with increasing pollution levels and that severe smog events promote the exposure.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In addition, the particulate matter also contained several bacteria that harbored antibiotic resistant genes flanked by mobile genetic elements, which could be associated with horizontal gene transfer.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Many of these bacteria were typical or putative members of the human microbiome.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The outdoor atmosphere harbors diverse microbial assemblages composed of bacteria, fungi and viruses whose functioning remains largely unexplored.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] While the occasional presence of human pathogens or opportunists can cause potential hazard, in general the vast majority of airborne microbes originate from natural environments like soil or plants, with large spatial and temporal variations of biomass and biodiversity.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Once ripped off and aerosolized from surfaces by mechanical disturbances such as those generated by wind, raindrop impacts or water bubbling, microbial cells are transported upward by turbulent fluxes.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Living airborne microorganisms may end up concretizing aerial dispersion by colonizing their new habitat, provided that they survive their journey from emission to deposition.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Bacterial survival is indeed naturally impaired during atmospheric transport, but a fraction remains viable.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] At high altitude, the peculiar environments offered by cloud droplets are thus regarded in some aspects as temporary microbial habitats, providing water and nutrients to airborne living cells.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In addition, the detection of low levels of heterotrophy raises questions about microbial functioning in cloud water and its potential influence on the chemical reactivity of these complex and dynamic environments.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] The metabolic functioning of microbial cells in clouds is still albeit unknown, while fundamental for apprehending microbial life conditions during long distance aerial transport and their geochemical and ecological impacts.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Aerosols affect cloud formation, thereby influencing sunlight irradiation and precipitation, but the extent to which and the manner in which they influence climate remains uncertain.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Marine aerosols consist of a complex mixture of sea salt, non-sea-salt sulfate and organic molecules and can function as nuclei for cloud condensation, influencing the radiation balance and, hence, climate.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] For example, biogenic aerosols in remote marine environments (for example, the Southern Ocean) can increase the number and size of cloud droplets, having similar effects on climate as aerosols in highly polluted regions.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Specifically, phytoplankton emit dimethylsulfide, and its derivate sulfate promotes cloud condensation.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Understanding the ways in which marine phytoplankton contribute to aerosols will allow better predictions of how changing ocean conditions will affect clouds and feed back on climate.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In addition, the atmosphere itself contains about 1022 microbial cells, and determining the ability of atmospheric microorganisms to grow and form aggregates will be valuable for assessing their influence on climate.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] They have formulated the hypothesis of the microbial formation of phosphine, envisaging the possibility of a liveable window in the Venusian clouds at a certain altitude with an acceptable temperature range for microbial life.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] However, in 2021 Hallsworth *et al.* examined the conditions required to support the life of extremophile microorganisms in the clouds at high altitude in the Venusian atmosphere where favorable temperature conditions might prevail.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Beside the presence of sulfuric acid in the clouds which already represent a major challenge for the survival of most of microorganisms, they came to the conclusion that the Venusian atmosphere is too dry to host microbial life.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] They determined a water activity ≤ 0.004, two orders of magnitude below the 0.585 limit for known extremophiles.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] While the physical and chemical properties of airborne particulate matter have been extensively studied, their associated airborne microbiome remains largely unexplored.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Microbiomes are defined as characteristic microbial communities, which include prokaryotes, fungi, protozoa, other micro-eukaryotes and viruses, that occupy well-defined habitats.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Throughout Earth's history, microbial communities have changed the climate, and climate has shaped microbial communities.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Microorganisms can modify ecosystem processes or biogeochemistry on a global scale, and we start to uncover their role and potential involvement in changing the climate.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] However, the effects of climate change on microbial communities (i.e., diversity, dynamics, or distribution) are rarely addressed.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In the case of fungal aerobiota, its composition is likely influenced by dispersal ability, rather than season or climate.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Indeed, the origin of air masses from marine, terrestrial, or anthropogenic-impacted environments, mainly shapes the atmospheric air microbiome.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] However, recent studies have shown that meteorological factors and seasonality influence the composition of airborne bacterial communities.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] This evidence suggests that climatic conditions may act as an environmental filter for the aeroplankton, selecting a subset of species from the regional pool, and raises the question of the relative importance of the different factors affecting both bacterial and eukaryal aeroplankton.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In 2020, Archer *et al.* reported evidence for a dynamic microbial presence at the ocean–atmosphere interface at the Great Barrier Reef, and identified air mass trajectories over oceanic and continental surfaces associated with observed shifts in airborne bacterial and fungal diversity.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Relative abundance of shared taxa between air and coral microbiomes varied between 2.2 and 8.8% and included those identified as part of the core coral microbiome.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Above marine systems, the abundance of microorganisms decreases exponentially with distance from land, but relatively little is known about potential patterns in biodiversity for airborne microorganisms above the oceans.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] Here we test the hypothesis that persistent microbial inputs to the ocean–atmosphere interface of the Great Barrier Reef ecosystem vary according to surface cover (i.e. land vs. ocean) during transit of the air-mass.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In 2021, researchers demonstrated that environmental DNA (eDNA) can be collected from air and used to identify mammals.
[src:bacterioplankton/aeroplankton] In 2023, scientists developed a specialized sampling probe and aircraft surveys to assess biodiversity of multiple taxa, including mammals, using air eDNA.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Several species of algae are raised for food.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Australian scientists at Flinders University in Adelaide have been experimenting with using marine microalgae to produce proteins for human consumption, creating products like "caviar", vegan burgers, meat substitute, jams and other food spreads.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] By manipulating microalgae in a laboratory, the protein and other nutrient contents could be increased, and flavours changed to make them more palatable.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] These foods leave a much lighter carbon footprint than other forms of protein, as the microalgae absorb rather than produce carbon dioxide, which contributes to the greenhouse gases.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Both microalgae and macroalgae are used to make agar.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] For centuries seaweed has been used as fertilizer.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] It is also an excellent source of potassium for manufacture of potash and potassium nitrate.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Some types of microalgae can be used this way as well.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] With concern over global warming, new methods for the thorough and efficient capture of CO2 are being sought out.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The carbon dioxide that a carbon-fuel burning plant produces can feed into open or closed algae systems, fixing the CO2 and accelerating algae growth.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Untreated sewage can supply additional nutrients, thus turning two pollutants into valuable commodities.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Waste high-purity CO2 as well as sequestered carbon from the atmosphere can be used, with potential significant benefits for climate change mitigation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Algae cultivation is under study for uranium/plutonium sequestration and purifying fertilizer runoff.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Business, academia and governments are exploring the possibility of using algae to make gasoline, bio-diesel, biogas and other fuels.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Algae itself may be used as a biofuel, and additionally be used to create hydrogen.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Microalgae are also researched for hydrogen production – e.g. micro-droplets for algal cells or synergistic algal-bacterial multicellular spheroid microbial reactors capable of producing oxygen as well as hydrogen via photosynthesis in daylight under air.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The BIQ House built in 2013 in Germany is a showcase experimental bionic house using glass facade panels for the cultivation of micro algae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Once the panels heat up thermal energy can also be extracted through a heat exchanger in order to supply warm water to the building.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The technology is still in an early stage and not yet fit for a wider use.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The Green Power House in Montana, United States used newly developed Algae Aquaculture Technology within a system that uses sunlight and woody debris waste from a lumber mill for providing nutrients to eight algae ponds of the AACT that cover its floor.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] In 2022, news outlets reported about the development of algae biopanels by a company for sustainable energy generation with unclear viability.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Seaweed grows in shallow and coastal areas, and captures significant amounts of carbon that can be transported to the deep ocean by oceanic mechanisms; seaweed reaching the deep ocean sequester carbon and prevent it from exchanging with the atmosphere over millennia.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Growing seaweed offshore with the purpose of sinking the seaweed in the depths of the sea to sequester carbon has been suggested.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] In addition, seaweed grows very fast and can theoretically be harvested and processed to generate biomethane, via anaerobic digestion to generate electricity, via cogeneration/CHP or as a replacement for natural gas.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Both macroalgae and microalgae are being investigated as possible means of carbon sequestration.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Marine phytoplankton perform half of the global photosynthetic CO2 fixation (net global primary production of ~50 Pg C per year) and half of the oxygen production despite amounting to only ~1% of global plant biomass.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Because algae lack the complex lignin associated with terrestrial plants, the carbon in algae is released into the atmosphere more rapidly than carbon captured on land.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Algae have been proposed as a short-term storage pool of carbon that can be used as a feedstock for the production of various biogenic fuels.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Large-scale seaweed farming could sequester significant amounts of carbon.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Wild seaweed will sequester large amount of carbon through dissolved particles of organic matter being transported to deep ocean seafloors where it will become buried and remain for long periods of time.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] With respect to carbon farming, the potential growth of seaweed for carbon farming would see the harvested seaweed transported to the deep ocean for long-term burial.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Seaweed farming occurs mostly in the Asian Pacific coastal areas where it has been a rapidly increasing market.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" on seaweed farming as a mitigation tactic.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Cultured strains of a common coral microalgal endosymbionts are researched as a potential way to increase corals' thermal tolerance for climate resilience and bleaching tolerance.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Cultured microalgae is used in research and development for potential medical applications, in particular for microbots such as biohybrid microswimmers for targeted drug delivery.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Cultivated algae serve many other purposes, including cosmetics, animal feed, bioplastic production, dyes and colorant production, chemical feedstock production, and pharmaceutical ingredients.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Most growers prefer monocultural production and go to considerable lengths to maintain the purity of their cultures.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] However, the microbiological contaminants are still under investigation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] With mixed cultures, one species comes to dominate over time and if a non-dominant species is believed to have particular value, it is necessary to obtain pure cultures in order to cultivate this species.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Individual species cultures are also much needed for research purposes.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] A common method of obtaining pure cultures is serial dilution.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Cultivators dilute either a wild sample or a lab sample containing the desired algae with filtered water and introduce small aliquots (measures of this solution) into a large number of small growing containers.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Dilution follows a microscopic examination of the source culture that predicts that a few of the growing containers contain a single cell of the desired species.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Following a suitable period on a light table, cultivators again use the microscope to identify containers to start larger cultures.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Another approach is to use a special medium which excludes other organisms, including invasive algae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] For example, *Dunaliella* is a commonly grown genus of microalgae which flourishes in extremely salty water that few other organisms can tolerate.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Alternatively, mixed algae cultures can work well for larval mollusks.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] First, the cultivator filters the sea water to remove algae which are too large for the larvae to eat.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Next, the cultivator adds nutrients and possibly aerates the result.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] After one or two days in a greenhouse or outdoors, the resulting thin soup of mixed algae is ready for the larvae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] An advantage of this method is low maintenance.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Water, carbon dioxide, minerals and light are all important factors in cultivation, and different algae have different requirements.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The basic reaction for algae growth in water is carbon dioxide + light energy + water = glucose + oxygen + water.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] It is also possible to grow certain types of algae without light, these types of algae consume sugars (such as glucose).
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] This is known as *heterotrophic* growth.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The water must be in a temperature range that will support the specific algal species being grown mostly between 15˚C and 35˚C.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] In a typical algal-cultivation system, such as an open pond, light only penetrates the top 3 to 4 inches (76–102 mm) of the water, though this depends on the algae density.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] As the algae grow and multiply, the culture becomes so dense that it blocks light from reaching deeper into the water.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] To use deeper ponds, growers agitate the water, circulating the algae so that it does not remain on the surface.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Paddle wheels can stir the water and compressed air coming from the bottom lifts algae from the lower regions.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Agitation also helps prevent over-exposure to the sun.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Another means of supplying light is to place the light *in* the system.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Glow plates made from sheets of plastic or glass and placed within the tank offer precise control over light intensity, and distribute it more evenly.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] They are seldom used, however, due to high cost.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The odor associated with bogs, swamps, and other stagnant waters can be due to oxygen depletion caused by the decay of deceased algal blooms.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Under anoxic conditions, the bacteria inhabiting algae cultures break down the organic material and produce hydrogen sulfide and ammonia, which causes the odor.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] This hypoxia often results in the death of aquatic animals.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] In a system where algae is intentionally cultivated, maintained, and harvested, neither eutrophication nor hypoxia are likely to occur.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Some living algae and bacteria also produce odorous chemicals, particularly certain cyanobacteria (previously classed as blue-green algae) such as *Anabaena*.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The most well known of these odor-causing chemicals are MIB (2-methylisoborneol) and geosmin.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] They give a musty or earthy odor that can be quite strong.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Eventual death of the cyanobacteria releases additional gas that is trapped in the cells.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] These chemicals are detectable at very low levels – in the parts per billion range – and are responsible for many "taste and odor" issues in drinking water treatment and distribution.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Cyanobacteria can also produce chemical toxins that have been a problem in drinking water.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Nutrients such as nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), and potassium (K) serve as fertilizer for algae, and are generally necessary for growth.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Silica and iron, as well as several trace elements, may also be considered important marine nutrients as the lack of one can limit the growth of, or productivity in, a given area.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Carbon dioxide is also essential; usually an input of CO2 is required for fast-paced algal growth.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] These elements must be dissolved into the water, in bio-available forms, for algae to grow.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] An open system of algae cultivation involves the growth of algae in shallow water streams which could originate from a natural system or artificially prepared.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] In this system, algae can be cultivated in natural water bodies like lakes, rivers, and in oceans, as well as artificial ponds made up of concrete, plastic, pond liners or variety of materials.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The open system of algae cultivation is simple and cost-effective, making it an attractive option for commercial production of algae-based products.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Open ponds are highly vulnerable to contamination by other microorganisms, such as other algal species or bacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Thus cultivators usually choose closed systems for monocultures.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Open systems also do not offer control over temperature and lighting.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The growing season is largely dependent on location and, aside from tropical areas, is limited to the warmer months.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Open pond systems are cheaper to construct, at the minimum requiring only a trench or pond.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Large ponds have the largest production capacities relative to other systems of comparable cost.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Also, open pond cultivation can exploit unusual conditions that suit only specific algae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] For instance, *Dunaliella salina* grow in extremely salty water; these unusual media exclude other types of organisms, allowing the growth of pure cultures in open ponds.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Open culture can also work if there is a system of harvesting only the desired algae, or if the ponds are frequently re-inoculated before invasive organisms can multiply significantly.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The latter approach is frequently employed by Chlorella farmers, as the growth conditions for Chlorella do not exclude competing algae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The former approach can be employed in the case of some chain diatoms since they can be filtered from a stream of water flowing through an outflow pipe.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] A "pillow case" of a fine mesh cloth is tied over the outflow pipe allowing other algae to escape.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The chain diatoms are held in the bag and feed shrimp larvae (in Eastern hatcheries) and inoculate new tanks or ponds.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Enclosing a pond with a transparent or translucent barrier effectively turns it into a greenhouse.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] This solves many of the problems associated with an open system.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] It allows more species to be grown, it allows the species that are being grown to stay dominant, and it extends the growing season – if heated, the pond can produce year round.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Open race way ponds were used for removal of lead using live *Spirulina (Arthospira) sp*.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] A lagoon is a type of aquatic ecosystem that is characterized by a shallow body of water that is separated from the open ocean by natural barriers such as sandbars, barrier islands, or coral reefs.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The Australian company Cognis Australia is a well-known company that specializes in producing β-carotene from *Dunaliella salina* harvested from hypersaline extensive ponds located in Hutt Lagoon and Whyalla.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] These ponds are primarily used for wastewater treatment, and the production of *D. salina* is a secondary benefit.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Open sea cultivation is a method of cultivating seaweed in the open ocean, as well as on a costal line in shallow water.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Seaweed farming industry serves commercial needs for various products such as food, feed, pharma chemicals, cosmetics, biofuels, and bio-stimulants.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Seaweed extracts act as bio-stimulants, reducing biotic stress and increasing crop production.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Additionally, it presents opportunities for creating animal and human nutrition products that can improve immunity and productivity.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Open ocean seaweed cultivation is an eco-friendly technology that doesn't require land, fresh water, or chemicals.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] It also helps mitigate the effects of climate change by sequestering CO2.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Open sea cultivation method involves the use of rafts or ropes anchored in the ocean, where the seaweed grows attached to them.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] This method is widely used for commercial seaweed farming, as it allows for large-scale production and harvesting.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The process of open sea cultivation of seaweed involves several steps.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] First, a suitable site in the ocean is identified, based on factors such as water depth, temperature, salinity, and nutrient availability.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Once a site is chosen, ropes or rafts are anchored in the water, and the seed pieces of seaweed are attached to them using specialized equipment.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The seaweed is then left to grow for several months, during which it absorbs nutrients from the water and sunlight through photosynthesis.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Raceway-type ponds and lakes are open to the elements.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] They are one of the most common and economic methods of large-scale algae cultivation, and offer several advantages over other cultivation methods.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] An open raceway pond is a shallow, rectangular-shaped pond used for the cultivation of algae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Because it is designed to circulate water in a continuous loop or raceway, allowing algae to grow in a controlled environment.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Open system is a low-cost method of algae cultivation, and it is relatively easy to construct and maintain.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The pond is typically lined with a synthetic material, such as polyethylene (HDPE) or polyvinyl chloride, to prevent the loss of water and nutrients.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The pond is also equipped with paddlewheels or other types of mechanical devices to provide mixing and aeration.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] High-Rate Algal Ponds (HRAPs) are a type of open algae cultivation system that has gained popularity in recent years due to their efficiency and low cost of operation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] HRAPs are shallow ponds, typically between 0.1 and 0.4 meters deep, that are used for the cultivation of algae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The ponds are equipped with a paddlewheel or other type of mechanical agitation system that provides mixing and aeration, which promotes algae growth.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] HRAP system is also recommended in wastewater treatment using algae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Algae can also be grown in a photobioreactor (PBR).
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] A PBR is a bioreactor which incorporates a light source.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Virtually any translucent container could be called a PBR; however, the term is more commonly used to define a closed system, as opposed to an open tank or pond.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Because PBR systems are closed, the cultivator must provide all nutrients, including CO 2.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] A PBR can operate in "batch mode", which involves restocking the reactor after each harvest, but it is also possible to grow and harvest continuously.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Continuous operation requires precise control of all elements to prevent immediate collapse.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The grower provides sterilized water, nutrients, air, and carbon dioxide at the correct rates.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] This allows the reactor to operate for long periods.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] An advantage is that algae that grows in the "log phase" is generally of higher nutrient content than old "senescent" algae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Algal culture is the culturing of algae in ponds or other resources.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Maximum productivity occurs when the "exchange rate" (time to exchange one volume of liquid) is equal to the "doubling time" (in mass or volume) of the algae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] PBRs can hold the culture in suspension, or they can provide a substrate on which the culture can form a biofilm.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Biofilm-based PBRs have the advantage that they can produce far higher yields for a given water volume, but they can suffer from problems with cells separating from the substrate due to the water flow required to transport gases and nutrients to the culture.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Flat panel PBRs consist of a series of flat, transparent panels that are stacked on top of each other, creating a thin layer of liquid between them.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Algae are grown in this thin layer of liquid, which is continuously circulated to promote mixing and prevent stagnation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The panels are typically made of glass or plastic and can be arranged in various configurations to optimize light exposure.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Flat panel PBRs are generally used for low-to-medium density cultivation and are well-suited for species that require lower light intensity and maximum surface area for optimum light exposure.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The temperature control in Flat panel PBR system is carried out by cooling down the culture in reservoir chamber using chilled water jacket as well as by sprinkling cold water on the flat panel surface.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Tubular PBRs consist of long, transparent tubes that are either vertically or horizontally oriented.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Algae are grown inside the tubes, which are typically made of glass or plastic.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The tubes are arranged in a helical or serpentine pattern to increase surface area for light exposure.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The tubing can be either continuously or intermittently circulated to promote mixing and prevent stagnation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Tubular PBRs are generally used for high-density cultivation and are well-suited for species that require high light intensity.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The temperature control in tubular PBR is a difficult task which is generally achieved by external sprinkling of deionized water which allow cooling of the tubes and subsequently reduces the temperature of culture circulating inside the tubes.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Biofilm PBRs include packed bed and porous substrate PBRs.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Packed bed PBRs can be different shapes, including flat plate or tubular.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] In Porous Substrate Bioreactors (PSBRs), the biofilm is exposed directly to the air and receives its water and nutrients by capillary action through the substrate itself.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] This avoids problems with cells becoming suspended because there is no water flow across the biofilm surface.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The culture could become contaminated by airborne organisms, but defending against other organisms is one of the functions of a biofilm.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] V-shaped plastic bags are commonly used in closed systems of algae cultivation for several reasons.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] These bags are made from high-density polyethylene (HDPE) and are designed to hold algae cultures in a closed environment, providing an ideal environment for algae growth.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] V-shaped plastic bags are effective for growing a variety of algae species, including *Chlorella*, *Spirulina*, and *Nannochloropsis*.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The growth rate and biomass yield of *Chlorella vulgaris* in V-shaped plastic bags was found to be higher than any other shaped plastic bags.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Different designs of plastic bags based PBR is developed from sealing the plastic bags at different places that generated, flat bottom hanging plastic bags, V-shaped hanging plastic bags, horizontally laying plastic bags that serves kind of flat PBR system, etc.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Many plastic bag-based designs are proposed but few are utilized on commercial scale due to their productivities.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Operation of plastic bags is tedious as they need to be replaced after every use to maintain the sterility, which is a laborious task for large scale facility.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Algae can be harvested using microscreens, by centrifugation, by flocculation and by froth flotation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Interrupting the carbon dioxide supply can cause algae to flocculate on its own, which is called "autoflocculation".
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] "Chitosan", a commercial flocculant, more commonly used for water purification, is far more expensive.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The powdered shells of crustaceans are processed to acquire chitin, a polysaccharide found in the shells, from which chitosan is derived via deacetylation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Water that is more brackish, or saline requires larger amounts of flocculant.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Flocculation is often too expensive for large operations.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Alum and ferric chloride are used as chemical flocculants.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] In froth flotation, the cultivator aerates the water into a froth, and then skims the algae from the top.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Ultrasound and other harvesting methods are currently under development.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Algae oils have a variety of commercial and industrial uses, and are extracted through a variety of methods.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Estimates of the cost to extract oil from microalgae vary, but are likely to be around three times higher than that of extracting palm oil.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] In the first step of extraction, the oil must be separated from the rest of the algae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The simplest method is mechanical crushing.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] When algae is dried it retains its oil content, which then can be "pressed" out with an oil press.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Different strains of algae warrant different methods of oil pressing, including the use of screw, expeller and piston.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Many commercial manufacturers of vegetable oil use a combination of mechanical pressing and chemical solvents in extracting oil.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] This use is often also adopted for algal oil extraction.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Osmotic shock is a sudden reduction in osmotic pressure, this can cause cells in a solution to rupture.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Osmotic shock is sometimes used to release cellular components, such as oil.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Ultrasonic extraction, a branch of sonochemistry, can greatly accelerate extraction processes.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Using an ultrasonic reactor, ultrasonic waves are used to create cavitation bubbles in a solvent material.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] When these bubbles collapse near the cell walls, the resulting shock waves and liquid jets cause those cells walls to break and release their contents into a solvent.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Ultrasonication can enhance basic enzymatic extraction.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Chemical solvents are often used in the extraction of the oils.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The downside to using solvents for oil extraction are the dangers involved in working with the chemicals.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Care must be taken to avoid exposure to vapors and skin contact, either of which can cause serious health damage.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Chemical solvents also present an explosion hazard.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] A common choice of chemical solvent is hexane, which is widely used in the food industry and is relatively inexpensive.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Benzene and ether can also separate oil.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Another method of chemical solvent extraction is Soxhlet extraction.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] In this method, oils from the algae are extracted through repeated washing, or percolation, with an organic solvent such as hexane or petroleum ether, under reflux in a special glassware.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The value of this technique is that the solvent is reused for each cycle.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Enzymatic extraction uses enzymes to degrade the cell walls with water acting as the solvent.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] This makes fractionation of the oil much easier.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] The costs of this extraction process are estimated to be much greater than hexane extraction.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Supercritical CO2 can also be used as a solvent.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] In this method, CO2 is liquefied under pressure and heated to the point that it becomes supercritical (having properties of both a liquid and a gas), allowing it to act as a solvent.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Other methods are still being developed, including ones to extract specific types of oils, such as those with a high production of long-chain highly unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:bacterioplankton/algaculture] Specific algal strains can be acquired from algal culture collections, with over 500 culture collections registered with the World Federation for Culture Collections.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] An **algal bloom** or **algae bloom** is a rapid increase or accumulation in the population of algae in fresh water or marine water systems.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] It may be a benign or harmful algal bloom.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Algal bloom is often recognized by the discoloration in the water from the algae's pigments.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The term *algae* encompasses many types of aquatic photosynthetic organisms, both macroscopic multicellular organisms like seaweed and microscopic unicellular organisms like cyanobacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] *Algal bloom* commonly refers to the rapid growth of microscopic unicellular algae, not macroscopic algae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] An example of a macroscopic algal bloom is a kelp forest.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Algal blooms are the result of a nutrient, like nitrogen or phosphorus from various sources (for example fertilizer runoff or other forms of nutrient pollution), entering the aquatic system and causing excessive growth of algae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] An algal bloom affects the whole ecosystem.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Consequences range from benign effects, such as feeding of higher trophic levels, to more harmful effects like blocking sunlight from reaching other organisms, causing a depletion of oxygen levels in the water, and, depending on the organism, releasing toxins into the water.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Yet, algae also play a crucial role by producing about 70 % of Earth's oxygen, which supports terrestrial life.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Blooms that can injure animals or the ecology, especially those blooms where toxins are secreted by the algae, are usually called "harmful algal blooms" (HAB), and can lead to fish die-offs, cities cutting off water to residents, or states having to close fisheries.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The process of the oversupply of nutrients leading to algae growth and oxygen depletion is called eutrophication.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Algal and bacterial blooms have persistently contributed to mass extinctions driven by global warming in the geologic past, such as during the end-Permian extinction driven by Siberian Traps volcanism and during the biotic recovery following the mass extinction (by delaying the recovery).
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The term *algal bloom* is defined inconsistently depending on the scientific field, and can range from a "minibloom" of harmless algae to a large, harmful bloom event.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Since *algae* is a broad term including organisms of widely varying sizes, growth rates, and nutrient requirements, there is no officially recognized threshold level as to what is defined as a bloom.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Blooms are the result of a nutrient needed by the particular algae being introduced to the local aquatic system.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] This growth-limiting nutrient is typically nitrogen or phosphorus, but can also be iron, vitamins, or amino acids.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] There are several mechanisms for the addition of these nutrients to the water.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] In the open ocean and along coastlines, upwelling from both winds and topographical ocean floor features can draw nutrients to the photic, or sunlit zone of the ocean.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Along coastal regions and in freshwater systems, agricultural, city, and sewage runoff can cause algal blooms.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Algal blooms, especially large algal bloom events, can reduce the transparency of the water and can discolor it.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The photosynthetic pigments in the algal cells, like chlorophyll and photoprotective pigments, determine the color of the algal bloom.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Depending on the organism, its pigments, and the depth in the water column, algal blooms can be green, red, brown, golden, or purple.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Bright green blooms in freshwater systems are frequently a result of cyanobacteria (colloquially known as "blue-green algae") such as *Microcystis*.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Blooms may also consist of macroalgal (non-phytoplanktonic) species.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] These blooms are recognizable by large blades of algae that may wash up onto the shoreline.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Once the nutrient is present in the water, the algae begin to grow at a much faster rate than usual.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] In a mini bloom, this fast growth benefits the whole ecosystem by providing food and nutrients for other organisms.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Of particular note are the harmful algal blooms (HABs), which are algal bloom events involving toxic or otherwise harmful phytoplankton.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Many species can cause harmful algal blooms.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Freshwater algal blooms are the result of an excess of nutrients, particularly some phosphates.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Excess nutrients may originate from fertilizers that are applied to land for agricultural or recreational purposes and may also originate from household cleaning products containing phosphorus.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The reduction of phosphorus inputs is required to mitigate blooms that contain cyanobacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] In lakes that are stratified in the summer, autumn turnover can release substantial quantities of bio-available phosphorus potentially triggering algal blooms as soon as sufficient photosynthetic light is available.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Excess nutrients can enter watersheds through water runoff.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Excess carbon and nitrogen have also been suspected as causes.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Presence of residual sodium carbonate acts as catalyst for the algae to bloom by providing dissolved carbon dioxide for enhanced photosynthesis in the presence of nutrients.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] When phosphates are introduced into water systems, higher concentrations can cause increased growth of algae and plants.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Algae tend to grow very quickly under high nutrient availability, but each alga is short-lived, and the result is a high concentration of dead organic matter which starts to decompose.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Natural decomposers present in the water begin decomposing the dead algae, consuming dissolved oxygen present in the water during the process.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] This can result in a sharp decrease in available dissolved oxygen for other aquatic life.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Without sufficient dissolved oxygen in the water, animals and plants may die off in large numbers.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Blooms may be observed in freshwater aquariums when fish are overfed and excess nutrients are not absorbed by plants.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] These are generally harmful for fish, and the situation can be corrected by changing the water in the tank and then reducing the amount of food given.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Algal blooms in freshwater systems are not always caused by human contamination and have been observed to occur naturally in both eutrophic and oligotrophic lakes.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Eutrophic lakes contain an abundance of nutrients such as nitrogen and phosphates which increase the likelihood for blooms.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Oligotrophic lakes don't contain much of these nutrients.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Oligotrophic lakes are defined by various degrees of scarcity.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The trophic state index (TSI) measures nutrients in freshwater systems and a TSI under 30 defines oligotrophic waters.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Algal blooms in oligotrophic bodies of water have also been observed.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] This is a result of cyanobacteria which cause blooms in eutrophic lakes and oligotrophic lakes despite the latter containing a lack of natural and man-made nutrients.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] A cause for algal blooms in nutrient-lacking environments come in the form of nutrient uptake.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Cyanobacteria have evolved to have better nutrient uptake in oligotrophic waters.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Cyanobacteria utilize nitrogen and phosphates in their biological processes.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Because of this, cyanobacteria are known to be important in the nitrogen and phosphate fixing cycle in oligotrophic waters.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Cyanobacteria can fix nitrogen by accessing atmospheric nitrogen (N2) that has been dissolved into water and transforming it into nitrogen accessible to other organisms.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] This higher amount of nitrogen is then able to sustain large algae blooms in oligotrophic waters.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Cyanobacteria are able to retain high phosphorus uptake in the absence of nutrients which help their success in oligotrophic environments.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Cyanobacteria species such as *D. lemmermannii* are able to move between the hypolimnion which is rich in nutrients such as phosphates and the nutrient-poor metalimnion which lacks phosphates.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] This causes phosphates to be brought up to the metalimnion and give organisms an abundance of phosphates, exacerbating the likelihood for algal blooms.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Upwelling events happen when nutrients such as phosphates and nitrogen are moved from the nutrient dense hypolimnion to the nutrient poor metalimnion.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] This happens as result of geological processes such as seasonal overturn when lake surfaces freeze or melt, prompting mixing due to changing water densities mixing up the composition of limnion layers and mixing nutrients around the system.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] This overabundance in nutrients leads to blooms.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Turbulent storms churn the ocean in summer, adding nutrients to sunlit waters near the surface.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] This sparks a feeding frenzy each spring that gives rise to massive blooms of phytoplankton.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Tiny molecules found inside these microscopic plants harvest vital energy from sunlight through photosynthesis.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The natural pigments, called chlorophyll, allow phytoplankton to thrive in Earth's oceans and enable scientists to monitor blooms from space.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Satellites reveal the location and abundance of phytoplankton by detecting the amount of chlorophyll present in coastal and open waters—the higher the concentration, the larger the bloom.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Observations show blooms typically last until late spring or early summer, when nutrient stocks are in decline and predatory zooplankton start to graze.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The visualization on the left immediately below uses NASA SeaWiFS data to map bloom populations.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The NAAMES study conducted between 2015 and 2019 investigated aspects of phytoplankton dynamics in ocean ecosystems, and how such dynamics influence atmospheric aerosols, clouds, and climate.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] In France, citizens are requested to report coloured waters through the project PHENOMER.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] This helps to understand the occurrence of marine blooms.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Wildfires can cause phytoplankton blooms via oceanic deposition of wildfire aerosols.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] A harmful algal bloom (HAB) is an algal bloom that causes negative impacts to other organisms via production of natural toxins, mechanical damage to other organisms, or by other means.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The diversity of these HABs make them even harder to manage, and present many issues, especially to threatened coastal areas.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] HABs are often associated with large-scale marine mortality events and have been associated with various types of shellfish poisonings.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Due to their negative economic and health impacts, HABs are often carefully monitored.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] HAB has been proved to be harmful to humans.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Humans may be exposed to toxic algae by direct consuming seafood containing toxins, swimming or other activities in water, and breathing tiny droplets in the air that contain toxins.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Because human exposure can take place by consuming seafood products that contain the toxins expelled by HAB algae, food-borne diseases are present and can affect the nervous, digestive, respiratory, hepatic, dermatological, and cardiac systems in the body.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Beach users have often experienced upper respiratory diseases, eye and nose irritation, fever, and have often needed medical care in order to be treated.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Ciguatera fish poisoning (CFP) is very common from the exposure of algal blooms.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Water-borne diseases are also present as our drinking waters can be contaminated by cyanotoxins.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] If the HAB event results in a high enough concentration of algae the water may become discoloured or murky, varying in colour from purple to almost pink, normally being red or green.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Not all algal blooms are dense enough to cause water discolouration.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Historically, forecasting algal blooms relied heavily on physical water sampling and hydrodynamic modeling.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] While accurate, these methods can be resource-intensive and struggle to rapidly process highly complex, changing environmental variables.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Consequently, modern forecasting increasingly integrates remote sensing with machine learning to complement traditional physical models.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Open-science initiatives have helped accelerate these algorithmic approaches.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] For example, during the 2019 NASA International Space Apps Challenge, a student team demonstrated how convolutional neural networks could analyze satellite data to predict cyanobacteria concentrations up to a month in advance.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] In formal scientific literature, recent frameworks employ self-supervised deep learning to fuse multi-sensor and hyperspectral satellite datasets.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] These models help generate early warning systems for coastal communities and water treatment facilities.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Despite these advancements, satellite-based forecasting faces inherent limitations.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Algorithmic accuracy depends heavily on accounting for highly localized factors, such as regional eutrophication or sudden water temperature shifts.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Furthermore, optical satellite measurements are frequently obstructed by cloud cover, requiring predictive models to rely on data interpolation to bridge missing gaps.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] There are three major categories for management of algal blooms consisting of mitigation, prevention, and control.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Within mitigation, routine monitoring programs are implemented for toxins in shellfish for early warnings and an overall surveillance of the area to monitor and quantify harmful algal blooms.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The HAB levels of the shellfish will be determined and can manage restrictions to keep contaminated shellfish off the food market.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Moving fish pens away from algal blooms is also another form of mitigation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Within prevention, we can reduce surface runoff carrying excess nutrients by increasing the amount of permeable surfaces and vegetation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Permeable surfaces help absorb the runoff before it can make its way into the waterway.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] We can put into place permeable streets and parking lots which help allow for the pollution from vehicles and other runoff nutrients to be soaked up and/or slowed.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Vegetation filters, absorbs, and slows the runoff which also helps to reduce the amount of excess nutrients making their way into the waterway.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Examples of planted vegetation to help reduce runoff include rain gardens, replacing grass with native plants, planting trees in yards and along waterways, and even rooftop gardens.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Farmers can reduce their impact on our waterways by planting cover crops, planting forested buffers, reducing their fertilizer use, and putting up fences to keep livestock out of streams.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Within control, there are mechanical, biological, chemical, genetic and environmental controls.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Mechanical control involves dispersing clay into the water to aggregate with the HAB leading to less of these HAB to go through the process of sedimentation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Biological control varies largely and can be used through pheromones or releasing sterile males to reduce reproduction.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Chemical control uses toxic chemical release.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] However, it may cause problems of mortality of other non targeted organisms.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Genetic control involves genetically engineering species in their environmental tolerances and reproduction processes.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] However, there are problems of harming indigenous organisms.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] For environmental control, it can use water circulation and aeration.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Harmful algae blooms have many negative environmental impacts and is a worsening issue that is spreading in area.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] A tiny brown tide organism that was formerly restricted to the northeastern US and South Africa, is now causing massive blooms along the coast of China which is similar to that of other brown tides.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] HABs can lead to anaerobic (lack of oxygen) environments which can kill any organisms living within the water, fish poisoning, respiratory problems and illness among beach goers.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] HABs have a large effect on the Great Lakes St.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Invasive zebra and quagga mussels are positively correlated with their impact on the environment.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] These mussels increase the cycling of phosphorus which therefore increases harmful algae blooms in areas they are present.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Harmful algae blooms continue to infect water supplies at the Binational Great Lakes Basin and due to the world's recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic, solving the issue has become a low priority.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] This economical problem has become part of politics in the United States, whereas in allied countries such as Canada there is low concern.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The impact of harmful algae blooms on the environment have a substantial effect on marine life.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] For example, in August 2024 the growth of the toxic algae, *Pseudo-nitzschia*, along California coasts were making sea lions sick and aggressive to beach goers.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Scientists claim this is a seasonal occurrence.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The growth of *Pseudo-nitzschia* leads to the production of a dominic acid which accumulates in fishes such as sardines, anchovies, and squids.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] This directly affects the food web and the primary food source of sea lions.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Once the toxins are transferred via consumption, they can cause seizures, brain damage, and death to the animal.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] During this surge, people reported bites and unpredictable, aggressive behavior from the infected sea lions.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] In this sickened state, the sea lions are scared and act out of fear in order to protect themselves.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Pregnant sea lions are most vulnerable to toxic algae poisoning and are more likely to die from the effects.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] In recent decades, the intensity and occurrence of algae blooms has increased.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] This is primarily due to the heating of oceans and other bodies of water, which stimulates algae growth, and also extends the growing season.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] However, climate change can also result in a decrease in algae blooms, due to intense rainfall that can flush the blooms out of bodies of water.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Moreover, the distribution of algae blooms has been predicted to expand north, particularly in the North Sea, in the next century.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Alongside climate change, the increase in algae blooms can be attributed to human practices.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] In agriculture, the use of fertilizers can provide the necessary nutrients for algae growth, and enter the water cycle from surface runoff.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] The first algal bloom in the world is *Eoseira wilsonii*.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-bloom] Dating back to the Eocene, it is the only known diatom to have algal blooms found in the Horsefly Shale and Eocene Okanagan Highlands.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Cyanobacteria found in sedimentary rocks indicate that bacterial life began on Earth during the Precambrian age.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Fossilized cyanobacteria are commonly found in rocks that date back to Mesoproterozoic.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Cyanobacteria are photoautotrophs in nature; they convert carbon dioxide and sunlight into food and energy via photosynthesis.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Some species are also able to fix atmospheric nitrogen and convert it into the biologically usable form of nitrate or nitrite.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] This gives them competitive advantage over other organisms that may be limited by the shortage of biologically available nitrogen.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] The cyanobacteria colonies contain two types of cells, the regular cells with chlorophyll carrying out the photosynthesis, and heterocysts which fix the nitrogen.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] These heterocysts have thick walls and lack chlorophyll, both of which limits their exposure to oxygen, the presence of which inhibits nitrogen fixation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] For the same reason, fixation may also be limited to nighttime when the light-dependent reactions of photosynthesis are shut down, minimizing oxygen production.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Stromatolites are alternating layers of cyanobacteria and sediments.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] The grain size of sediment portion of stromatolites is affected by the depositional environment.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] During the Proterozoic, stromatolites' compositions were dominated by micrite and thinly laminated lime mud, with thicknesses no greater than 100 microns.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Modern stromatolites are characterized by their thicker and more irregular laminations due to coarser grain size.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Stromatolites trap sediment particles when the particles come to a rest from wave agitation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Trapping is separate process where filaments of bacteria traps the particle, provided the angle of the filaments are still within the limits before the grain rolls off due to overcoming the friction of the film.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] The length of the cyanobacterial filaments plays an important role in deciding the grain size trapped.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] It has been noted that these bacterial mats were marked by geochemical areas, such as volcanism and tectonics.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] They favour harsh environments that are either nutrient-depleted or have high salinity levels.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] This resilience may also be due to the autotrophic lifestyle of the bacteria, which enables them to thrive in a variety of harsh environments.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Algal mats consist largely of filaments made of autotrophic bacteria and fine-grained particles.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] These bacterial are well known for the formation of stromatolites.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Phototrophic bacteria such as cyanobacteria are evolutionary organisms responsible for the increased oxygen levels during the Proterozoic age.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] The event was known as The Great Oxidation Event, during which complex eukaryotic life forms originated, potentially due to the increased oxygen availability.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Preserved stromatolites are called stromatoliths.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] They can be easily recognized by their crystallized, thinly laminated layers and their domed, columnar or conical shapes.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] However, the same cannot be said for stromatolites that were not crystallized.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] The lack of many well-preserved stromatolites has been proposed as a consequence of ongoing diagenesis during formation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Diagenesis is a weathering process where newly deposited sediments lies on top of the old sedimentary bed, buried and compacted, lithified and uplifted to the surface as sedimentary rocks.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] The rapid formation of algal mats can result in harmful algal blooms (HABs), also known as red tides or green tides.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] HABs have been known to produce a wide range of toxins, with newer toxins discovered frequently, which makes the task of understanding these phenomena increasingly difficult.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] HABs can be found in water of high importance for economic and environment; with salinity ranging from low to high such as in rivers and lakes to reservoirs and oceans.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Toxins can seep into the water column, from which they may be introduced into the local water supply, affecting humans and livestock.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Toxins can have either direct or indirect effects on an organism.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Some marine life is directly susceptible to toxins caused by HABs, while others are affected through accumulation of toxins over a period of time.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] This bioaccumulation process typically affects organisms such as filter-feeding shellfish and secondary consumers.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] It has been estimated that there are thousands of human poisoning cases annually in Asia from toxic water.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Single HAB fish-kill events in Korea have been estimated to have cost millions of dollars, and in Japan such events have been estimated to have resulted in losses of fish worth more than $300 million.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Moreover, some HABs are harmful to the ecosystem simply by their sheer biomass accumulation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Such biomass accumulation can lead to a multitude of negative consequences.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] For one, their growth and proliferation can reduce the light penetration in the water column, thereby reducing habitat suitability for the growth of submersed grasses.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Exceedingly high biomass can also cause fish gills to clog, leading to suffocation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] High biomass blooms can also lead to the development of “dead zones”, formed when the algae begin to die and their decomposition depletes the water of oxygen.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Dead zones are unable to support (aerobic) aquatic life, and are responsible for losses of millions of dollars’ worth of fish annually.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Third generation biofuel feedstocks are represented by both micro- and macro- algae, which present further advantages over the previous generations.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] (The first generation biofuels are made from edible feedstock like corn, soybean, sugarcane, and rapeseed.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Second generation of biofuels from waste and dedicated lignocellulosic feedstock shave advantages over those of first generation.) Marine and aquatic biomass tentatively demonstrates high yield while requiring minimal use of arable land.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-mat] Major advantages of algae are: no competition with food crops for arable land, high growth rates, and low fractions of lignin which reduces the need for energy-intensive pretreatment and compatibility with biorefinery approach implementation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Algal nutrient solutions are made up of a mixture of chemical salts and seawater.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Sometimes referred to as "Growth Media", nutrient solutions (e.g., the Hoagland solution, along with carbon dioxide and light), provide the materials needed for algae to grow.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Nutrient solutions, as opposed to fertilizers, are designed specifically for use in aquatic environments and their composition is much more precise.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] In a unified system, algal biomass can be collected by utilizing carbon dioxide emanating from power plants and wastewater discharged by both industrial and domestic sources.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] This approach allows for the concurrent exploitation of the microalgae's capabilities in both carbon dioxide fixation and wastewater treatment.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Algae, macroalgae, and microalgae hold promise in addressing critical global challenges.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Sustainable development goals can be advanced through algae-based solutions, to promote a healthy global ecosystem.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] There are two infrastructures for creating algae-based solutions: open ponds/raceway ponds or Photo-Bio Reactors (PBRs).
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Photobioreactors are becoming more prevalent in the cultivation of algae, particularly for the production of valuable resources and small-scale experimental applications.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Recently, there has been an increased consideration of using photobioreactors for large-scale algal biomass production, driven by their ability to create ideal growth conditions.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Enclosed reactors offer protection against bacterial contamination, and the use of shallow tubing ensures effective utilization of light.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] The infusion of CO2 through bubbling enhances the efficiency of carbon uptake, while the design minimizes water loss.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] In comparison to raceway ponds, photobioreactors exhibit significantly higher rates of productivity.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Raceway ponds, much like the oxidation ditches utilized in wastewater treatment systems, are expansive open basins distinguished by their shallow depths and lengths that far exceed their widths.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Typically, they are constructed with a concrete shell lined with polyvinyl chloride (PVC), boasting dimensions that vary from 10 to 100 meters in length and 1 to 10 meters in width, with depths ranging from 10 to 50 centimeters.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Oswald, was a figure in the field of environmental engineering, particularly known for his contributions to wastewater treatment and algal cultivation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Oswald is renowned for his research on the use of algae in wastewater treatment.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] He advocated for the integration of algal ponds with wastewater treatment plants as a cost-effective and environmentally friendly method for nutrient removal and biomass production.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] In the 1950s, Oswald championed the open pond as the most feasible approach to integrate algal cultivation with wastewater treatment.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] His work in the 1950s and beyond helped pave the way for the development and implementation of algal-based treatment systems worldwide.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] To make the most of the biomass, it's crucial to efficiently gather the algae at the start of the processing stage.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] The method chosen for harvesting depends on the type of algae being grown.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Microalgae, with their small cell size, need more advanced harvesting techniques compared to larger macroalgae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Often, a combination of methods is used to achieve a final biomass that has the right moisture content.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Common ways to harvest algae include using microfilters, causing particles to clump together (flocculation), allowing them to settle (sedimentation), using flotation, and employing centrifuges.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Biodiesel stands as a promising contender in relation to traditional fossil diesel fuel.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] The rapid growth, boasting up to 4–6 harvest cycles annually, presents a notable advantage.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Unlike predecessors in biofuel production, macroalgae thrive in aquatic environments, sidestepping concerns over land use and freshwater consumption.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] It surpasses terrestrial biomass in several aspects: yielding higher levels of carbohydrates and biomass, enjoying widespread availability, and avoiding competition with food crops or arable land.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] The quality of their by-products adds to their appeal.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Notably, their capacity to sequester CO2 and integrate seamlessly into wastewater treatment processes enhances the sustainable energy initiative aspect.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Macroalgae thrive in diverse environments, from saltwater to municipal wastewater, requiring neither arable land nor industrial fertilizers.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Moreover, they can be harnessed for biomethane production through thermal or biological gasification, offering flexibility in biomass selection.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] In recent years, significant attention has focused on the potential of microalgae as a biofuel source.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Microalgae, yielding between 19,000 – 57,000 liters of oil per acre annually, surpassing other forms of biodiesel resources.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] This oil is then transformed into biodiesel using conventional transesterification methods.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] The residual biomass harbors valuable components such as lipids, proteins, and soluble polysaccharides.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] These components can be leveraged for the production of bio-oil, bioethanol, biohydrogen, and biogas through diverse thermochemical and biochemical pathways, thereby enhancing the overall energy balance.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Algae can also serve as an alternative food source for humans.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] It typically boasts abundant protein levels, particularly in red varieties like Pyropia tenera, where it may constitute as much as 47% of the dry mass.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] These proteins are valuable not only as a dietary protein source, providing essential amino acids, but also for their bioactive properties, including specific enzymes.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Algae is an alternative for gelatin and can also be a much more natural/healthier source for creating low carb, gluten and fat-free foods.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Algae presents a distinct advantage over traditional food and feed sources, as it does not compete with them and does not require changes in land use.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] This characteristic makes algal-based fuels a promising solution to alleviate the food versus fuel dilemma in the future.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Unlike other biofuels, algal feedstock remains unaffected by fluctuations in food market prices, ensuring greater price stability for consumers of algal-based fuel.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Algae possess significant promise due to their rapid growth rate and exceptional yield per hectare, surpassing that of land-based biomass by a considerable margin.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Renowned as the swiftest proliferating organisms on Earth, they can reproduce within mere hours.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Research conducted underscores their remarkable capacity, demonstrating growth rates 20–30 times faster than food crops and yielding up to 30 times more fuel than alternative biofuel sources.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Algae exhibits geographical versatility, capable of thriving in diverse climates, including the most severe environments on Earth.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] They demonstrate adaptability across varying altitudes, latitudes, and geographies, without the need for agriculturally productive or environmentally sensitive land for reproduction.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Unlike energy crops like oil palm and rapeseed, which have sparked sustainability concerns due to food versus fuel competition and land occupation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Algae does not compete with crops for arable land and can utilize wastelands unsuitable for agriculture owing to their ability to adapt to harsh environments.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Furthermore, the adaptability enables survival in industrial, municipal, and agricultural wastewaters, as well as on landfills, facilitating wastewater treatment by nutrient removal such as nitrogen (N) and phosphorus (P), thereby contributing to community access to clean water.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Within aquatic ecosystems, algae assumes a pivotal role by utilizing photosynthesis to transform water and carbon dioxide into sugar, concurrently releasing oxygen as a by-product.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] However, inadequate management can create significant environmental consequences.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] One outcome is the manifestation of algae blooms or eutrophication, primarily triggered by runoff from land sources.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] This leads to an excessive nutrient influx, fostering the overgrowth of algae.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Upon the decay of these algal blooms, bacteria consume a substantial amount of dissolved oxygen, depleting oxygen levels in the water.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] This occurrence can result in the formation of dead zones or hypoxia, characterized by minimal or no oxygen, rendering them unsuitable for aquatic life.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Although open ponds can be used for algae cultivation, they are low production which can take year-round development.PBRs are mainly for small scale use despite their high-productivity.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] The limitations also stem from their high energy and cost demands during both production and operation phases.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Unlike alternative infrastructure, PBRs require significantly larger surface areas for the volume of algal broth, leading to greater material volumes and subsequent spikes in capital energy input.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] These factors elevate environmental impacts associated with their implementation.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Despite the immense potential of both macro- and microalgae in various fields, the production cost of algal fuel remains higher compared to fossil fuels.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Although strides have been made in reducing nutrient costs by utilizing wastewater and flue gases, the expenses associated with mechanical equipment and technologies remain substantial.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Essentially, the foundational processes involved in the production and commercialization of algae biofuels persist as significant barriers.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Similarly, effectively utilizing chemicals, technology, electricity, and labor for microalgal biofuel production poses considerable challenges.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Cultivating microalgae in both closed and open reactors under optimal pH, temperature, and light conditions is crucial for achieving rapid biomass doubling and high productivity.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] The complex procedures involved in processing algae cells pose limitations on their use as a feedstock for biodiesel production.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Hence, researchers must prioritize addressing these challenges and enhancing production efficiency.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Essential for algal development are solar light, carbon dioxide, water, and various nutrients such as nitrogen, sulfur, phosphorus, and iron.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] However, ensuring the availability of these nutrient sources and maintaining suitable environmental conditions amidst changing climatic patterns presents sustainability challenges.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Cost is another significant hurdle, as the expenses associated with growing and harvesting algae are considerable.
[src:bacterioplankton/algal-nutrient-solution] Utilizing wastewater for cultivating algae emerges as one cost-effective strategy.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Bacterioplankton occupy a range of ecological niches in marine and aquatic ecosystems.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] They are both primary producers and primary consumers in these ecosystems and drive global biogeochemical cycling of elements essential for life (e.g., carbon and nitrogen).
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Many bacterioplankton species are autotrophic, and derive energy from either photosynthesis or chemosynthesis.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Photosynthetic bacterioplankton are often categorized as picophytoplankton, and include major cyanobacterial groups such as *Prochlorococcus* and *Synechococcus*.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Other heterotrophic bacterioplankton are saprotrophic, and obtain energy by consuming organic material produced by other organisms.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] This material may be dissolved in the medium and taken directly from there, or bacteria may live and grow in association with particulate material such as marine snow.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Bacterioplankton play critical roles in global nitrogen fixation, nitrification, denitrification, remineralisation and methanogenesis.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Bacterioplankton abundance depends on environmental variables like temperature, nutrient availability and predation.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Like other small plankton, the bacterioplankton are preyed upon by zooplankton (usually protozoans), and their numbers are also controlled through infection by bacteriophages.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Photosynthetic bacterioplankton are responsible for a large proportion of the total primary production of aquatic food webs, supplying organic compounds to higher trophic levels.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] These bacteria undergo oxygenic and anoxygenic photosynthesis.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Differences between these processes can be seen in the byproducts produced, the primary electron donor, and the light harvesting pigments used for energy capture.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Cyanobacteria are a large group of photosynthetic bacterioplankton, often growing as cells or in filamentous colonies.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] These organisms are the dominant group of bacterioplankton using oxygenic photosynthesis in aquatic ecosystems.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Cyanobacteria, along with photosynthetic eukaryotes, are responsible for approximately half of the total global primary production making them key players in the food web.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] They use photosynthesis to generate energy in the form of organic compounds and produce oxygen as a byproduct.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Major light harvesting pigments include chlorophylls, phycoerytherin, phycocyanin and carotenoids.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The majority of cyanobacteria found in marine environments are represented by the genera *Synechococcus* and *Prochlorococcus.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Synechococcus* is cosmopolitan, having been reported across temperate and tropical waters.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] *Prochlorococcus* is a very small in size and is found mainly in the euphotic zone of tropical waters.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Factors including light, nutrients, and temperature can cause cyanobacteria to proliferate and form harmful blooms.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Cyanobacteria blooms can cause hypoxia and produce high levels of toxins, impacting other aquatic organisms as well as causing illnesses in humans.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Some Cyanobacteria are capable of nitrogen fixation.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The genus *Anabaena* uses specialized cells called heterocysts to physically separate nitrogen fixation and photosynthesis.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] *Trichodesmium* is an example of cyanobacteria that is capable of fixing nitrogen through an alternative photosynthetic pathway.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Other photosynthetic bacterioplankton, including purple and green bacteria, undergo anoxygenic photosynthesis in anaerobic conditions.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The pigments synthesized in these organisms are sensitive to oxygen.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] In purple bacteria the major pigments include bacteriochlorophyll a and b and carotenoids.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Green bacteria have different light harvesting pigments consisting of bacteriochlorophyll c, d and e.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] These organisms do not produce oxygen through photosynthesis or use water as a reducing agent.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Many of these organisms use sulfur, hydrogen or other compounds as an energy source to drive photosynthesis.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Most of these bacterioplankton are found in anoxic waters, including stagnant and hypersaline environments.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Heterotrophic bacterioplankton rely on the available concentration of dissolved organic matter in the water column.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Usually these organisms are saprophytic, absorbing nutrients from their surroundings.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] These heterotrophs also play a key role in the microbial loop and the remineralization of organic compounds like carbon and nitrogen.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Pelagibacterales (synonym SAR11), also known as members of an *Alphaproteobacteria* clade, are the most abundant bacterioplankton in the oceans.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Members of this group are found in waters with low nutrient availability and are preyed on by protists.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Atmospheric carbon is sequestered into the ocean by three main pumps which have been known for 30 years: the solubility pump, the carbonate pump, and the biological carbon pump (BCP).
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The biological carbon pump is a vertical transmission pump driven mainly by the sinking of organic rich particles.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Bacterial phytoplankton near the surface incorporate atmospheric CO2 and other nutrients into their biomass during photosynthesis.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] At the time of their death these phytoplankton, along with their incorporated carbon, sink to the bottom of the ocean where the carbon remains for thousands of years.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The other biologically mediated sequestration of carbon in the ocean occurs through the microbial pump.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The microbial pump is responsible for the production of old recalcitrant dissolved organic carbon (DOC) which is >100 years old.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Plankton in the ocean are incapable of breaking down this recalcitrant DOC and thus it remains in the oceans for 1000s years without being respired.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The two pumps work simultaneously, and the balance between them is believed to vary based on the availability of nutrients.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Overall, the oceans act as a sink for atmospheric CO2 but also release some carbon back into the atmosphere.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] This occurs when bacterioplankton and other organisms in the ocean consume organic matter and respire CO2, and as a result of the solubility equilibrium between the ocean and the atmosphere.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The nitrogen cycle in the oceans is mediated by microorganisms, many of which are bacteria, performing multiple conversions such as: nitrogen fixation, denitrification, assimilation, and anaerobic ammonia oxidation (anammox).
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] There are many different nitrogen metabolism strategies employed by bacterioplankton.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Starting with molecular nitrogen in the atmosphere (N2), which is fixed by diazotrophs such as trichodesmium into usable forms like ammonia (NH+ 4).
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] This ammonia can then be assimilated into organic matter like amino and nucleic acids, by both photoautrophic and heterotrophic plankton, it can also be nitrified to NO− 3 for energy production by nitrifying bacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Finally the use of NO− 3 or NO− 2 as terminal electron acceptors reduces the nitrogen back into N2, which is then released back into the atmosphere thus closing the cycle.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Another important process involved in the regeneration of atmospheric N2 is anammox.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Anammox, a process in which ammonia is combined with nitrite in order to produce diatomic nitrogen and water, could account for 30–50% of production of N2 in the ocean.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] An analysis on metagenomes of 83 species of cyanobacteria has suggested the possible dissimilatory nitrate reduction to ammonium (DNRA) activity in certain cyanobacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Namely, the study found the presence of the *NirBD* gene, which is a marker for DNRA function, in the families Leptolyngbyaceae and Nostocaceae.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Moreover, the study indicated that the cyanobacteria that had *NirBD* are largely also non-heterocyst nitrogen fixers, suggesting possible alternative strategies of acquiring nitrogen under varying environmental conditions.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Nonetheless, the *NirBD* gene is also known to play a role in nitrogen assimilation and further studies are required to ascertain the function of *NirBD* in cyanobacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Dissolved organic matter (DOM) is available in many forms in the ocean, and is responsible for supporting the growth of bacteria and microorganisms in the ocean.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The two main sources of this dissolved organic matter are; decomposition of higher trophic level organisms like plants and fish, and secondly DOM in runoffs that pass through soil with high levels of organic material.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The age and quality of the DOM is important for its usability by microbes.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The majority of the DOM in the oceans is refractory or semi-labile and is not available for biodegradation.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] As mentioned above the microbial pump is responsible for the production of refractory DOM which is unavailable for biodegradation and remains dissolved in the oceans for thousands of years.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The turnover of labile DOM organic material is quite high due to scarcity, this is important for the support of multiple trophic levels in the microbial community.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The uptake and respiration of DOM by heterotrophs closes the cycle by producing CO2.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Bacterioplankton, such as members of *Roseobacter*, SAR11, and *Gammaproteobacteria*, are known to contribute significantly towards the sulfur cycle, primarily through the metabolism of dimethylsulfoniopropionate (DMSP).
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] DMSP can be catabolized either via means of cleavage to dimethylsulfide (DMS) or demethylation by bacterioplankton, in which both have contrasting effects on the sulfur cycle.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The formation of DMS contributes to the sulfur flux into the atmosphere and according to the CLAW hypothesis, plays a role in regulating global climate.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Increased production of sulfate aerosols from DMS oxidation are capable of promoting cooling on a global scale, via the promotion of cloud formation.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] In contrast, the demethylation pathway from DMSP to methanethiol results in the integration of carbon and sulfur into the organism itself as opposed to releasing the elements back to the environment.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Bacterioplankton DMSP degradation is thought to be prevalent in marine surface waters, although the spatial distribution of the two aforementioned routes of degradation exhibit high variation.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Similar to DNRA, the same study indicated the presence of a *dsyB*-like gene in certain cyanobacteria genomes, suggesting DMSP producing ability.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] However, there has yet to be empirical confirmation of DMSP synthesis in cyanobacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Diatoms are a major group of phytoplankton in which most have a requirement for silicon as biogenic silica to form their cell wall (known as frustule).
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Upon predation or death, particulate silica is released from diatoms but they need to be dissolved for recycling and reuptake by diatoms, otherwise silica will be exported out and deposited into sediment.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Hence, the productivity of diatoms will be limited by silicon if dissolution rates are slow.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] However, it is known that bacterioplankton (i.e. members of *Cytophaga-Flavobacterium-Bacteroides*, *Alphaproteobacteria*, and *Gammaproteobacteria*) significantly promote the dissolution of particulate silica, thus maintaining the significant biogenic silica production in the ocean photic zone.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] It is also suggested that this process helps regulate diatom productivity and its corresponding biogeochemical effects.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Variations in bacterioplankton abundance are usually a result of temperature, zooplankton grazing, and availability of substrate.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Bacterial abundance and productivity are consistently related to algal abundance and productivity as well as organic carbon.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] In marine pelagic environments, heterotrophic nano-flagellates are the most probable consumers of bacterial cell production.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Cultured flagellates in laboratory experiments demonstrate that they are adapted to predation on bacteria-sized particles and occur in concentrations to control bacterial biomass.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Tight fluctuations in numbers of bacteria and flagellates have been found in a eutrophic estuary, particularly in the summer.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The amplitude of these fluctuations increases in response to artificial eutrophication with inorganic nutrients and decreases in response to predation.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Losses of bacterioplankton by grazing is indirectly related to carbon balances and directly related to prokaryotic inhibitors.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] A surplus of substrate would cause increased flagellate biomass, increased grazing on bacterioplankton and therefore decreased bacterial biomass overall.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Predation of ciliates is analogous to predation by flagellates on bacteria as well.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] With using prokaryotic inhibitors seasonally, there is a positive relationship between bacterial abundance and heterotrophic nanoplankton grazing rates and only 40-45 % of bacterioplankton production was observed to be consumed by phagotrophic Protozoa.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Additionally, eukaryotic inhibitory experiments show that protozoan grazing has a positive effect on bacterioplankton production suggesting that nitrogen regeneration by Protozoa could be highly important for bacterial growth.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Eukaryotic inhibitors did not prove to be useful to determine protozoan grazing rates on bacterioplankton, however they may help understand control mechanisms in the microbial food web.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Bacterioplankton such as cyanobacteria are able to have toxic blooms in eutrophic lakes which can lead to the death of many organisms such as fish, birds, cattle, pets and humans.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] A few examples of these harmful blooms is the *Microcystis* bloom in the year 2000 in Swan River estuary, Australia, and the Oostvaarderplassen in the Netherlands in 2003.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] The detrimental effects of these blooms can range from heart malformation in fish to constraining copepod reproduction.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] High temperatures caused by seasonality increases stratification and preventing vertical turbulent mixing which increases competition for light that favours buoyant cyanobacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Higher temperatures also reduce the viscosity of water which allows faster movement which also favors buoyant species of cyanobacteria.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] These species are also very competitive with the ability to create a surface cover preventing light to reach deeper species of plankton.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Climate studies are also indicating that with increasing heat waves the likelihood of detrimental cyanobacterial blooms will become more of a threat to eutrophic freshwater systems.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Other implications of the increasing average air temperature due to climate change is that there might be an expansion of the cyanobacterial bloom season, extending from earlier in the spring to later in the fall.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Estimates of bacterioplankton abundance and density can be derived with a variety of methods including direct counts, flow cytometry, and conclusions drawn from metabolic measures.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] Further, as discussed in the biogeochemical cycling section, plankton are responsible for the recycling and movement of essential nutrients (i.e. nitrogen/carbon/DOM) which are essential building blocks for many of the organisms co-existing with bacterioplankton in these ecosystems.
[src:bacterioplankton/bacterioplankton] These recycled nutrients can be reused by primary producers, thus increasing the efficiency of the biological food web and minimizing energy waste.
